{"key":"post-12653447","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12653447</id>\n<content>If it's really hot in summer, it's a good idea to change the soak water for fresh cold tap water half way through.&amp;nbsp; We used to use the refrigerator to help prevent bacteria bloom during the soak, but as long as the soak water isn't too warm, that's not a problem.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The consolidation phase allows the mycelium to consume some of the nutrients, storing them for the flush.&amp;nbsp; If you fail to consolidate with brf cakes, they're so nutritious that you often get nothing but blobs of mutant tissue with no caps on first flush.&amp;nbsp; This is because optimal nutrition levels for colonization are higher than for fruiting.&amp;nbsp; It sounds counter-intuitive, but you actually want less nutrients in the fruiting stage.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12653468</next>\n<prev>12652666</prev>\n<first>12652438</first>\n<last>12703282</last>\n<when>1275198144</when>\n<utime>05/30/10 08:42 AM</utime>\n</post>"}